column1: Which current candidate for the U.S. House of Representatives will the Center for Responsive Politics list as having raised the most money this election cycle?
column11: This question will be suspended on 5 November and resolved using data retrieved on 1 December 2018 from Opensecrets.org, and by selecting "Current Candidates Only" (e.g., Jon Ossoff is not a current candidate) and "Current Cycle Only." Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Data tabulated to resolve this question is open until 12/1/18. Trone currently has a significant but not insurmountable lead.
OpenSecrets Top 3: Trone, David (D) (Maryland District 06) $16,524,302 Wallace, Scott (D) (Pennsylvania District 01) $13,925,299 Nunes, Devin (R)* (California District 22) $11,643,750
Trone has a huge lead for the house but I think there is still a chance that one of the three behind him could raise a lot suddenly.
Per 538's analysis, wealthy candidates Wallace and Cisneros apparently are in tight election races; Trone and Nunes may not be...:
Nunes and Wallace funding totals move up a little higher as of 10/28/18: https://www.opensecrets.org/overview/topraise.php?cycle=2018&display=S&view=topraise&type=C2
Mr. Money man Trone! His "consultants" must be in money heaven looking to cash the famouos 10% commision of all those ads and 20% management fee!

Based on numbers from opensecrets.org, Trone (1st) has nearly a $2.6 million lead over Wallace (2nd). 538.com projects a 99% chance of Trone winning so doubtful to see much of a spike in fundraising leading up to final days of the election.

Not observing significant changes at the top of the funding 'scoreboard' thus far, as election day draws closer. https://www.opensecrets.org/overview/topraise.php?cycle=2018&display=S&view=topraise&type=C2
6 million is a massive gap, and consensus also thinks so.
Not currently forecasting it, but large, late contributions to -- or from -- one of the top candidates could still conceivably change the $$'s "scoreboard".
"More info" says "..."Current Candidates Only" (e.g., Jon Ossoff is not a current candidate) and "Current Cycle Only."
Sticking with my analysis. Damn the unknown unknowns, full steam ahead.
Have *NOT* confirmed these are the top 4. I have confirmed Ossoff is not a 'current candidate' if you are wondering why his name isn't on the list.
